As y'all know, I love taking pictures. I try to use the best and most interesting for the blog, but they represent maybe 5% or 10% of all the photos I take. The rest are for Laurie and me to look at through the winter and remember special times and places. Sometimes I get asked what kind of camera I use, so here's a post to reveal my secrets.

Whenever we're out at popular tourist sites, I see folks hauling around huge DSLR cameras, with a big bag full of lenses and equipment. Look at the camera below: do you know how heavy this is, not counting the additional lenses in the bag? No, thanks.

<a href="http://zumsteg.us/?attachment_id=7211" rel="attachment wp-att-7211"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-7211" src="http://zumsteg.us/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/dslr.jpeg" alt="" width="400" height="235"></a>I thought some folks might like to see my camera:

<a href="http://zumsteg.us/?attachment_id=7214" rel="attachment wp-att-7214"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-7214" src="http://zumsteg.us/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/IMG_4650-2.jpg" alt="" width="864" height="648"></a>This is a Sony RX100M3. I got it not long before the trip to replace my older Sony RX100M2, which went into a lake with me when a canoe I was in capsized. &nbsp;I looked at other more sophisticated cameras but decided to go with what I knew. No bag required: I carry this in a small case on my belt.

This is a pretty top-of-the-line point-and-shoot camera; in terms of picture resolution it holds its own against dang good SLRs. Later versions of this camera have a much longer telephoto capability, but they trade off something I value and use a lot: at the wide-angle end of the lens' range the camera has a 28mm capability and a 1.8 f-stop. That means I can take pictures in very low light; the cameras with lots of telephoto capability do not have the ability to take low-light pictures without a flash. And before I bought my first RX100 five years ago I tracked how often I used a long lens and it wasn't very often, so I don't miss that capability.

This camera also has an easy-to-use manual capability, meaning I can set the shutter speed and f-stop to suit unusual situations. I don't need that often, but it's invaluable when I run into some odd light situation.

This camera has a ton of bells and whistles; certainly all that I ever need. When I see someone carting around $5,000 worth of camera and lenses in a big bag slung over their shoulder, I'm reminded that the great photographers of the earlier days - Ansel Adams, Georgia O'Keefe, Edward Weston, Alfred Stieglitz, Annie Leibovitz, Diane Arbus - used what were essentially glorified box cameras, with not the first automatic feature. It isn't the equipment that makes good photos, it's the photographer.&nbsp;

As for "post-processing" (messing around with a picture in the computer to make it look better), I use Adobe's Lightroom. I'm a bit of a traditionalist about this: I don't do anything I couldn't do in a well-equipped darkroom. I crop the picture if necessary, adjust the exposure and contrast, clean up perspective on buildings - all things I could do in a dark room.&nbsp;

See? No secrets. I think we can take really good pictures without spending a fortune on equipment. If there is a secret to taking good pictures, it's "Love the picture you're taking." I try to take a picture only if I love what I'm seeing and want others to love it, too, through the picture.

